Q27: This final question is optional. Do you think that the quality of participants varies as a function of time of semester and/or method of recruitment? If so, how?
{"ImportId":"QID34_TEXT"}

If the effect I'm investigating is so fragile that it'd disappear depending on the time of the semester or recruitment method, then I should probably be looking into another area of research. A friend of mine published a nice paper a couple years ago replicating a bunch of basic effects in cognition (i.e., Stroop, Switching, Flanker, Simon, Posner Cuing, attentional blink, subliminal priming, and category learning tasks) using MTurk subjects: http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0057410

I'm familiar with the belief that participants recruited at the start of the semester perform better (i.e., with higher motivation/attention to the task) than participants recruited at the end of the semester. However, I only rarely recruit from the undergraduate subject pool and am uncertain as to the status of this claim.

Common observations include: last-minute-course credit students are less conscientious and less care about research; and community participants who come to the experiments have less familiarity of psychology tests.
Also, the composition of participants can also be different depending on the method of recruitment. Usually there are more international students than domestic students when the study provides financial payment - this may influence (1) task comprehension, and (2) task performance (may have better scores on number related tasks but lower scores on reading/language based tasks).
Yes. Reduced effort in later parts of the semester. This appears to lead to higher rates of poor performance/needing to exclude participants.
I think the quality of participants declines sharply from the middle of semester on.

Q17: The role of confidence in learning under uncertianty
Q27: Being closer to exam time may make observers more eager to finish the task, and they may respond with less caution. However it is also possible that in becoming more studious around exam times, observers are more attentive and respond with greater caution, in retrospect to my answers. I don’t have solid empirical evidence to support my inferences - this is just my intuition based on testing REP students vs paid observers
Time of semester is unlikely to have an effect. Online introduces more variance but also offers opportunity for generalizability and overcoming low-power problems with small N.

Q17: semantic priming; word recognition; mental lexicon

Q27: Yes. More effortful and engaged students at the beginning of semester.

Yes. During the final two weeks of the semester, in-lab participants are less cautious and less accurate on speeded tasks that have previously reported very high accuracy (90%). On non-speeded tasks, participant RT remains stable, while accuracy decreased. 
Online studies have reported differences, with fewer participants completing the study once testing has commenced online than in-lab, and accuracy tending to be lower online than in-lab. We have not noted a difference in response times between our online and in-lab studies, yet!
Yes
For subject pool: YES. For the other participants, there is no noticeable changes in performance relative to the moment in the semester.

Yes - selection bias - students who sign up for experiments early in the semester likely differ from those who wait for the last moment in their conscientiousness, attention, desire to please the experimenters, etc. Online participants can be less interested in the experiment itself or in the abstract value of contributing to science and can be less conscientious as a result.

Yes, I think that participants recruited via MTurk are less reliable as we cannot control what they do at the same time (e.g., be on the phone, listen to music). Regarding undergraduate students, I think that only those sign up for studies in the first few weeks that have enough time and are motivated enough. In the last few weeks, they only sign up if they still need credit.

Somewhat. 
When I did more active recruitment I tended to see some shifts in variance on parameters, not so much shifts in mean performance. Average issue undergraduates do, in my opinion, tend to go more quickly then people from the broader community but don't, in my work, show very different learning. I have done less work with online recruitment but have been positively surprised by the data quality in the studies I have done.

It should not. Try to minimize deception.
If anything, participants are most suspicious with moderate experience. They have been fooled a couple of times and want to find the experimenters trick. When very experienced they do not care anymore.

Yes. Participants recruited later in the semester frequently appear to be ones who have put off running experiments until the last minute, and/or who are less interested in running experiments relative to getting their course credit. They also tend to have more coursework responsibilities later in the semester, so their time is at a premium.
Have found that undergraduates who sign up to studies early in the semester tend to be more motivated students
Quality of student ps certainly does in my experience. The motivated students take part early. Towards the end of the term students just go through the motions.

Yes, definitely. Generally, my personal observation has been that students at the end of the semester skip their scheduled experiment appointments much more frequently than students earlier in the semester. Students at the end of the semester also seem much more agitated and as if they are unhappy or "forced" to come do experiments; my impression is that this mindset leads them to be more careless about the experiment instructions and task, leading to very poor quality. For this reason I always stop collecting data using undergraduates (even paid ones) before the last 3 weeks of classes. It would be a waste of time and money.
yes, student motivation changes over the course of the term. Also, different type of people participate at different times (more conscientious individuals might participate sooner)

Yes. I believe that for student samples--where the students are meeting a subject pool requirement--the quality declines somewhat at the very end of the semester. I do not have a good sense of how strong an effect this is, though.

Q17: Reasoning, Categorization, Memory, High-level cognition, Cognitive Development
Q27: Yes. Our Department rewards those undergraduates who complete all of their experimental participation requirement in the first half of semester with bonus points. These students are typically better organised and more motivated than those who participate late - and their data is typically less noisy

For undergrads, I believe that motivation and fatigue are key factors to data quality. At the end of semester, I find that students are more likely to stack together experimental sessions and so they're more likely to be fatigued to complete your experiment.
Yes I do - I published a paper on this topic, showing participants perform differently on selective attention based on reimbursement and time of semester

To me, it definitely seems *possible* that the quality of participants varies throughout the semester. Anecdotally, it does often seem to be the case that the more academically committed students complete their credit points earlier in the semester, but I'm not sure if this would empirically hold. I think assessing data at different times of the semester would be a very interesting empirical question to study, though

Also, on a slightly unrelated note, I found the definition of "well" and "poorly" to be a bit ambiguous in the survey. When I answered the questions, I took "participants performing the task well" to mean "participants providing data that is an accurate reflection of their true nature/ability". However, after reading the second question about caution, I figure that you actually meant "participants having high task ability" (i.e., high drift rate in terms of response time models). Therefore, you may wish to exclude my answers based on this

I believe the experimenter must spend more time and be more careful in encouraging participants to focus and perform well, depending on the time of day and time of semester. However, given sufficient encouragement, performance should be comparable.

I would expect lower quality data from online experiments as you cannot control what else they are doing, or their conditions. Students doing it for course credit may also be less motivated, especially those who leave it til later, than members of the public who volunteer.

Q17: Memory, false memories, psych and law
Q27: I think it does for students. I think students at the end of the semester produce terrible quality data which probably shouldn’t be used in analyses.

Overall, I do not think the quality of data from undergrads varies much (if at all) over the course of the semester. There are likely to be some differences (men are more likely to participate later, people with a job are more likely to participate later, older people are more likely to participate later) but these small differences rarely result in observable differences on cognitive tasks. Perhaps a personality researcher should be concerned with semester effects, but most researchers likely don't need to be concerned.

Yes - undergrads left in the pool at the end of semester are usually low quality responders

From my experience, student samples can be unreliable - depending maybe not on time, but on whether they need credits to pass the course or not or how the quality of their responses are checked. My experience is with students from teaching programs, who were not very enthusiastic about cognitive tasks we used in several studies with them.
Somewhat - a small percentage of student participants seem to be extremely sleep-deprived during the last few weeks, and so I suspect that their performance would be somewhat worse.

Yes, we tend to get participants that are less motivated and less interested in participating later in the semester. This is especially if they are doing the experiment for course credit. It is likely they are picking random experiments out of those remaining in the list later in the semester.

Dependimg on the measured variables. For instance I expect students to be specially anxious/ depressed/ stressed at the end of the semester as oposed to the beginning. However, other measures (i.e. political leanings or reaction times) I don’t expect to vary too systematically.
